he File System Why is the important? Every time you use a computer, you are interacting with files and folders â€” even if you donâ€™t notice it. Your photos, essays, songs, and documents are all files, and the file system is what keeps them organized. Without a file system, it would be impossible to find, save, or open anything on your computer. For anyone using technology to solve problems, this knowledge is essential because every solution you create will likely need to save, load, or organize files. Misunderstanding how file systems work often leads to errors like â€œfile not found.â€ Knowing how to navigate and organize files is a core problemâ€‘solving skill for using computers effectively. What is a File? A file is a collection of information stored on a computer. Files can contain text (essays), images, music, videos, or apps. Every file has a name and usually an extension (e.g., .docx , .jpg , .mp3 ) indicating its type. What is a File System? A file system is how a computer organizes and keeps track of files. Think of it like a library: Books â†’ files Shelves & sections â†’ folders Catalog system â†’ file system The file system makes sure files donâ€™t get lost, you can find them quickly, and apps know where to look for information. File System Example (Tree Diagram) /Home\n â”œâ”€â”€ Documents\n â”‚    â”œâ”€â”€ Assignments\n â”‚    â”‚    â””â”€â”€ lab1.txt\n â”‚    â””â”€â”€ essay.docx\n â”œâ”€â”€ Pictures\n â”‚    â””â”€â”€ photo.jpg\n â””â”€â”€ Music\n      â””â”€â”€ song.mp3 How to read this: Home is the root folder. Documents , Pictures , and Music are subfolders. Files like lab1.txt , essay.docx , photo.jpg , and song.mp3 live inside those folders. Absolute Path An absolute path starts from the very top of the file system (the root ). It always tells the full route to a file and always starts with / . /Home/Documents/Assignments/lab1.txt / = root ( Home ) Documents â†’ folder inside Home Assignments â†’ folder inside Documents problem_solve0.txt â†’ file Relative Path A relative path starts from your current location in the file system. . = current folder .. = one folder up (parent) Examples (starting in /Home/Documents ): Assignments/lab1.txt          â† go down into Assignments\n..                            â† go up to /Home\n../Pictures/photo.jpg         â† up one, then into Pictures Quick Comparison Absolute Path Relative Path Always starts at root / Starts from current location Works no matter where you are Depends on where you are Longer, but less ambiguous Shorter, but contextâ€‘sensitive Tools You'll Need A simple text editor like: Notepad (Windows) TextEdit (Mac â€” make sure it's in plain text mode!) ðŸ¥ Go to: Format --> Make plain text For more instructions on macOS, visit this document Or a free editor like Notepad++ or VS Code Set your editor to use a monospaced font like Courier. This ensures all characters take up the same width and height which is very important for keeping your art aligned! Your Task Open a new text file and create two pieces of ASCII art: One small image that fits in a 5x5 grid (5 characters wide Ã— 5 lines tall) One larger image that fits in a 10x10 grid (10 characters wide Ã— 10 lines tall) You can do this on pen and paper or you can try using this web based tool . You can draw anything you like (e.g., faces, animals, robots, trees, symbols,...) as long as it fits in the grid and follows the guidelines. Now that weâ€™re starting to work with and create files, set up a special folder on your computer to store all of your coursework for this class. This will keep your work organized and easy to find for future assignments. Place the text file containing your ASCII art into this folder. For extra organization, you can create a subfolder (e.g., named Labs or Problem-Solving Work ) to hold your lab activities separately from other coursework. Write down both the absolute path and the relative path as if you are starting inside the Desktop folder (pretend your current locatio