53	2652184	Lab: Problem Solve 4	ITSC 1212 Problem Solve 4 Overview and Instructions Overview Up to now, weâ€™ve been exploring ideas step by step, now youâ€™ll start putting them together in code using Strype to build Python programs. What is Strype? Strype is a free, web-based editor that lets you write real Python code using frames. Each frame represents a step or instruction and together they build your program. Additionally each frame is a complete statement or block of code, so you can focus on logic instead of worrying about syntax and indentation errors. Remember that this is your first time seeing and using this new tool to actually write a program during lab. . Donâ€™t worry if it feels unfamiliar at first; the goal is to experiment, practice, and get comfortable with the basics of programming in this environment. Instructions Using this Google Doc template compile your solutions in a single document to submit for this lab. Task 1: Meet Strype Go to https://strype.org Links to an external site. in your browser and click "Start coding now!" Explore the three main sections in the code area: Imports â€“ bringing in libraries Function definitions â€“ defining reusable code My code â€“ where the main part of your code runs 3. The main idea behind Stype is frames. A frame in Strype is a building block of code.Instead of typing raw text (like in a normal text code-editor), you insert frames, and each frame contains one complete, valid statement or structure in Python.Think of frames like Lego bricks: Each brick has a defined shape (e.g., a print() statement, an if condition, or a loop). You can connect bricks together in a sequence to build a program. Some bricks are â€œcontainersâ€ (like if or for ) and allow other frames to be placed inside them. 4. Frames appear in the frame palette under â€œMy projectâ€ tab on the right side of the screen. The frame palette shows all the frames that can be added at each place based on the Python grammar. The symbols on the lef