ariable is a named reference that can change. >>> a = 1\n>>> c = a + 5\n>>> print(c) Update a variable: >>> b = 2\n>>> print(a + b)\n3\n>>> b = 5\n>>> print(a + b)\n6 Your tasks: At the IDLE prompt, assign a variable x = 10 . Then update it using x = x + 5 . Record the final value of x . Create a constant PI = 3.14159 . Use it to calculate the circumference of a circle with radius 4. Show your formula and your code. As a reminder the formula to calculate the circumference of a circle is c = 2 Ï€r . Try to create a variable with an invalid name (e.g., 2bad = 5 ). Take a screenshot of your IDLE window showing your interaction, output and the error message from the previousÂ step and add it to your Google Doc. Note #1 : In programming, a constant is simply a variable that you intend not to change once itâ€™s given a value. Unlike some languages (like Javaâ€™s final), Python does not enforce this rule, thereâ€™s no built-in way to stop you from reassigning a constant. Instead, programmers follow a naming convention: constants are written in ALL_CAPS with underscores between words, such as: >>> PI = 3.14159 >>> DAYS_IN_WEEK = 7 >>> TAX_RATE = 0.08 This signals to others (and reminds you) that the value should stay fixed. Note #2: Naming rules & conventions (Python) Start with a letter or underscore; then letters, digits, underscores. Case-sensitive; cannot use keywords (e.g., for , if , class ). Style (PEP 8): snake_case for variables ( hours_worked ), UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants ( DAYS_IN_WEEK ). Task 5 Casting (type conversion) Use constructors: int(x) â†’ integer (truncates toward zero ) float(x) â†’ float str(x) â†’ string bool(x) â†’ boolean truthiness >> print(7.3)\n>>> print(int(7.3))          # 7\n>>> print(7.3 * 2.5)\n>>> print(int(7.3) * 2.5)    # int first, then multiply\n>>> print(int(7.3 * 2.5))    # multiply first, then int() Remember to use round(x, ndigits) if you want rounding instead of truncation. Your tasks: At the IDLE prompt, convert the string "