om a former student's (Mariah Olsen's) research project: It wasnâ€™t until 2001 that Dr. Markus Raichle pointed out a network of areas in the brain that seemed to turn off whenever someone focused on a particular task and back on again when no task was at hand. His observation unleashed a plethora of research about the brainâ€™s default, â€œtask-negative,â€ network, and over the next ten years it became apparent that these areas of the brain are involved in very personal, identity-related thought processes (para. 12). To provide evidence for claims you're making. Most people don't know that egg farmers practice debeaking, or "beak trimming" as it is referred to in the United Egg Producers' 2017 "Guidelines for US Egg-Laying Flocks" (p. 9). . . . The United Egg Producers acknowledge this in their guidelines: "Under certain management systems (e.g., exposure to high intensity natural lighting) and with some genetic stocks, beak trimming/treatment may be required" (p. 9). When a source says something so well that you simply can't improve it by paraphrasing. E.g. As Lamott (1994) so honestly states, "Very few writers really know what they are doing until they've done it" (p. 301). Step 2: Read Before You Write For this assignment, please start by reading the above examples (all about quoting). Then--to distinguish between quoting, paraphrasing, and summarizing--please skim "Quoting, Paraphrasing, and Summarizing." Then read THIS chapter from They Say/I Say: The Moves That Matter in Academic Writing (pp. 43â€“44) . Focus on the templates for introducing quotes. (Tip: These templates will guide your practice.) Intro to Quoting Well Step 3: Practice with Quotes Open a Google Doc and complete the following: Part A. Introducing Quotes Choose two quotes from your Research Log sources and one quote from a course reading (or another from your log). Use a They Say/I Say template to introduce each quote. Add 1â€“2 sentences explaining the quote in your own words. You can color code the templates like I did in the examples below. E.g. In his book Mercy for Animals , RunkleÂ maintains that "[f]ish deserve to be more than food. They deserve our compassion." Runkle's point is that fish are smart, social, sentient beings who deserve to be treated as such. Part B. APA Citation Practice For each of your three quotes, add an APA in-text citation . Make sure you try both: Narrative citation (Author, year, p. # appears within your sentence). Parenthetical citation (everything in parentheses at the end). E.g. In his book Mercy for Animals , Runkle (2017) maintains that "[f]ish deserve to be more than food. They deserve our compassion" (p. 73). Runkle'sÂ point is that fish are smart, social, sentient beings who deserve to be treated as such. You'll notice that in APA, it is typical to introduce the author and to cite the year early in the sentence, and then you only have to cite the p. or para. number at the end of the sentence. It is possible to save the author's last name for the end, in which case your citation would look like this: In the book MercyÂ for Animals , the authorÂ maintains thatÂ "[f]ish deserve to be more than food. They deserve our compassion" (Runkle, 2017, p. 73). Runkle'sÂ point is thatÂ fish are smart, social, sentient beings who deserve to be treated as such. However, I'd like you to get into the habit of introducing your sources BEFORE you quote from them because that is conventional in academic writing and is expected by your readers. Basically, your readers expect to know whose words they're reading before they're reading them. They don't want to be wondering whose words they're reading, and they don't want to be surprised by a citation at the end of a sentence. Be clear about who and what you're quoting, right off the bat. Part C. Reflection At the end of your Doc, write a short response (4â€“5 sentences): Which template felt most natural to you? Which was hardest to use, and why? What questions do you still have about quotin