rd "purpose." "What is your argument here?" means "What is your purpose for writing this?") rhetorical situation (not in video) : t he situation you find yourself in as a writer who has to produce a text or as a reader who has to consume a text The last term in the list above implies that studying rhetoric is helpful to us as writers and as readers. You can read and write with rhetorical awareness. I.e. an awareness of the choices the writer made while writing. Why did this writer use these words? Why did this writer open this essay with an anecdote? Why does this writer rely so heavily on hyperbole? What can I do to further my point in this essay? When studying rhetoric, the first step to analyzing your rhetorical situation (as a reader or a writer) is the rhetorical triangle. Note : You just learned that rhetoric has its roots in ancient Greece where they studied public speech. That's why you often see "speaker" and "audience" instead of "writer" and "readers," but these terms are interchangeable. Consider, for instance, how your writing changes based on your reader. You wouldnâ€™t write an e-mail to me asking for a deadline extension using the same language you would use in a text to your best friend asking for a ride to campus. You will adapt your writing to fit your rhetorical situation, based on the parts of your triangle. âœ… Step 2: Brief Reflection In your Google folder, create a document titled "Threshold Concepts Reflection." Write 3â€“5 bullet points responding to these prompts: What does rhetoric mean, in your own words? Whatâ€™s one example of how you change your language based on who you're talking to? Why might it be useful to think about writing and reading rhetorically? Threshold Concepts (15â€“20 minutes) All fields or disciplines of study, including Writing Studies, have what educators call threshold concepts . You just learned about one of Writing Studies' threshold concepts, rhetoric . Understanding a threshold concept is moving to a different 