1	244951	202580-Fall 2025-HIST-1575-008-American Democracy	HIST 1575: Foundations of American Democracy Fall 2025 Course: HIST 1575 Location and Time: MWF 9:05 -9:55 am; Denny 111 Instructor: Dr. Morgan Gray Office: Garinger 101 Office Hours : MWF 11:15 am â€“ 12:15 pm or by appointment (in person); on Zoom by appointment Email: mgray60@charlotte.edu INTRODUCTION TO THE COURSE Welcome to Foundations of American Democracy! In this course, weâ€™ll focus on the founding documents and use them as a basis for understanding movements for equality and civil rights throughout US history (but especially post-Civil War). Many of the basic themes may be familiar to you from your past education, but many of these narratives are much more complex than you may have seen before. In addition to continuing to develop your reading and writing skills, you will learn how to manage inaccessible language, a little bit about US law and social justice, and a LOT about the way that race, gender, class, and religion intersect. Regardless of your major, what you learn here will help you understand the world around you and participate in it more mindfully. COURSE DESCRIPTION When looked at through a justice-oriented lens, modern US history can be described as a process of working to apply equal rights to all. This course will examine this process, using the founding legal documents as an origin point, and considering the critical role of activists as well as evolving social dynamics and legal norms. In so doing, it will reveal both the real and imagined power of these documents and the importance (and challenges) of creating equality in the modern US context. THE CHARLOTTE CORE: THEME COURSES Being able to work and collaborate with diverse groups of people and to approach problems creatively are skills that employers want and that you need to succeed in college and your daily life. The Charlotte Core provides you with many opportunities to develop this engagement across perspectives competency in your Global and Local Theme courses, major, and co-curricular activities. This Local Theme course plays an important role in the Charlotte Core. It focuses on engaging students with the world in which they live as both individuals as well as members of society. You will learn the following engagement across perspectives skills while practicing critical thinking. Ask questions about familiar and unfamiliar communities and/or cultures Discuss cultural similarities and differences in perspectives, behaviors, expressions, and/or communication styles across space and/or time Interpret events, issues, problems, etc. from multiple perspectives Other Theme courses and courses in your major will build on the skills you develop in this class and provide you with even more opportunities to practice them. The Global Theme Courses (1501 and 1502) engage issues related to areas outside of the United States. The Local Theme Courses (1511 and 1512) engage issues related to areas within the United States. Assignments from this course may be used for general education continuous learning improvement regarding the competencies. All identifying information will be removed. Local Theme Local Themes Courses address the question: what does it mean to be a member of a local community, with a focus on: Appreciating what is different and understand what is similar in the experiences and expressions of different peoples, cultures, and communities in our city, our state, our region, and our nation Exploring how local structures (power dynamics, economic capacity, social capital) and cultural traditions (forms of expression, religious and ethnic identities, lines of thought) frame peopleâ€™s experiences and the choices they make Identifying areas of commonality and contest that play out in the interactions between different groups in the town, city, state, region and country LEARNING OUTCOMES Our collective goals for the class are as follows: GUIDING QUESTIONS: What are the founding principles of American democracy? How have ideas of freedom, equality, and power changed since the founding of the country until the present? How has our understanding of democracy changed since the founding of the country? Is America exceptional? What does that mean? TECHNICAL SKILLS: Analytical writing Close reading Teamwork/collaboration Working to deadlines Written and oral communication LOCAL THEME OBJECTIVES: Ask questions about familiar and unfamiliar communities and/or cultures Discuss cultural similarities and differences in perspectives, behaviors, expressions, and/or communication styles across space and/or time Interpret events, issues, problems, etc. from multiple perspectives COMMUNICATING WITH ME The only way to successfully finish the semester together is to communicate, and communication is a two-way street. I will let you know about changes to the syllabus or to assignments (in addition to the classroom lessons themselves). In return, I would like you all to let me know if you have questions, or if problems arise that make it harder for you to participate in the class. Here are some great ways to get in touch with me: Canvasâ€™s Message feature or via email : For all your standard communication needs. I will reply in 24-48 hours, depending on how many other emails I have. If you donâ€™t hear from me in 48 hours, youâ€™re welcome to send me a polite follow-upâ€” it is entirely possible for emails to get lost in my inbox! Office hours: Office hours are my commitment to be in my office and available, so this is the best way to talk with me one-on-one. If you want me to look at a draft with you, to answer questions in a more detailed way, or just to chat about something, come on into my office. Iâ€™ll be there between 11:15 am and 12:15 pm on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday: no appointment necessary! If you canâ€™t visit during those times, thatâ€™s okay. You can email me, and we can find a time that works for both of us. If you would prefer to meet via Zoom, I am happy to accommodate you. Just email me to set that up. Chatting after class: I always stick around after class while we pack up to leave, precisely so that you all can stop to ask questions or chat on the way out the door. Itâ€™s a great chance to ask for a quick clarification, to let me know of an impending absence, or just to say hi. RESPECT AND GROUP DISCUSSIONS While this course is technically a lecture course, you will find that we have a variety of opportunities to discuss and explore the themes of the course, both in small groups and as a class. These discussion formats are not designed to call anyone out or cause embarrassment, but rather to give you other ways to engage with the course concepts and to learn from one another. This may mean that you encounter ideas that generate some discomfort; that is often a normal part of intellectual growth! However, I will do my best to warn you of any potentially intense topics ahead of time, and you are always welcome to quietly excuse yourself if you need some breathing space. I would also encourage you to come and speak to me in office hours or to email me if you have any concerns. Respect is critical to these discussion-based interactions; comments should never be meant personally, so that your colleagues can learn not to take them personally. Feel free to disagree and debate appropriately with the class (even with me!), but freedom of speech does not grant you the privilege of being rude or making personal attacks. This holds doubly true for disrespect based on race, ethnicity, gender, sexual orientation, religion, disability, or any other identity. Diversity of experience and culture is essential to the field of history! COURSE MATERIALS For this class, you will need to purchase the following things: -Â Â Â Â Â Â  The 1575 Reader (published by the UNC Charlotte History Department) Access to Packback Both of these materials should be available to you with your Niner Course Pack and must be purchased through the campus bookstore , but if you are unable to access them for any reason, please talk with me ASAP! We will also use a free, online (open source) textbook occasionally; links to that will be available in Canvas as needed. Other materials include: Notetaking materials: This can be either a pen/pencil and paper, or a computer/tablet. Please use whichever format will allow you to learn and retain information. I will not allow you to use your phone or laptop to take notes in class (see below), so please make sure that you have an alternate strategy! Paper and something to write with : Even if you prefer to use a tablet for your notes, you will still need paper and a writing tool to complete in-class assignments and quizzes. Access to a computer and internet connection: You will submit all your materials online for this class, so there is no need for you to worry about printing costs. However, you will need to use a computer to type your papers and access assignments on Canvas. You will also need to access all our readings electronically. UNCC has a variety of computer labs available for students, as well as Wi-Fi. If you are having trouble accessing the necessary technology for any reason, please let me know ASAP so that we can get you what you need. A NOTE ABOUT TECHNOLOGY! This is a tech-friendly classroom, but I do have limitations. You may only have your laptops out during specific activities (I will give you permission). This is to help keep distractions to a minimum and give you a chance to practice your note-taking skills. I will make exceptions for people with specific accommodations, so make sure you talk to me if that applies to you! I will not police your cell phone use (youâ€™re adults!), but I do expect that you will adhere to a few basic rules of professional courtesy. Keep scrolling, tweeting, DMing, texting, and surfing to a minimum. Sending a quick text or checking a notification is perfectly alright, especially if itâ€™s fairly urgent (e.g., a work or family situation). Openly scrolling while someone else is talking? Nope, rude. Please donâ€™t do that. NO HEADPHONES, EARBUDS, OR EARPODS ARE ALLOWED IN CLASS. Why? Because it sends the message that youâ€™d rather be listening to something/someone else. Even if thatâ€™s true (and I expect it will be at least some of the time), itâ€™s inconsiderate to the speaker(s) to show that. Life is going to be full of things youâ€™d rather not be doing, but that are still important to be present for. I will make exceptions for people with specific accommodations, so make sure you talk to me if you need to have access to your headphones for any reason! If you receive a phone call that you must take, I will expect you to step out into the hallway, just as if you were in a professional meeting. No need to make a big deal out of it, just step out and step back in. Please do not FaceTime or video call in class. If your technology use becomes a distraction to me or to other students, I reserve the right to ask you to change your behavior. ASSIGNMENTS With the exception of our first mini-assignment (which will be submitted online) and your Packback reading discussions, all of our writing assignments and tests will be completed IN CLASS on paper. I have chosen this method because of a combination of factors: 1) I want to make sure that you are producing work from your own memory and knowledge, not the internet; 2) it allows me to build skills with you in a very concrete way; and 3) it helps me to motivate students to attend class regularly. Because many of these assignments are in class, they will technically be timed (since they are limited by the class period). I design in-class assessments to be completed in 50-60% of the class period; however, if you have an accommodation that includes extra time on tests and/or the need to type your responses rather than handwrite them, I will work with you to make sure that you have what you need. Writing Assessments: You will complete 10 writing assessments (â€œmini-assignmentsâ€) for me over the course of the semester. These will be worth 20 points each (or 20% of your final grade). Most of these will be completed in class and will help you build the skills you need to read and write at a higher level. In general, we will do these assignments on Fridays, though there may be exceptions as the schedule evolves. Packback: Packback is a software that facilitates more active discussions than a standard Canvas Discussion Board. The software will guide you through writing a strong discussion question, and then you will respond to two of your colleauges. You will complete one of these per week (minus the first and last weeks of the term), and they will be worth roughly 15% of your final grade. Packback does do the grading for me, but ultimately I make the final determination of your grade. I will also read the weekly reports and may use your questions to facilitate class discussions! More information about Packback and how it works can be found on Canvas. I am also happy to answer any questions or uncertainties you may have. Exams and Tests: You will take 4 unit tests for me (worth 25 points each), and one final â€œblue bookâ€ exam (worth 100 points). Together, these account for 20% of your final grade. I will provide guidance and study guides as we get closer to these dates. For now, remember that the goal of these evaluations is to help you show me what you know, not to trick you or punish you! MAJOR DUE DATES: GRADING NOTE: I do not offer extra credit! These are your only opportunities to earn points towards your final grade, so take them all seriously, even if theyâ€™re not â€œbig ticketâ€ assignments. GRADING SCALE 90-100 A 80-89Â Â  B 70-79Â Â  C 60-69Â Â  D 0- 59Â Â Â  F I will do my best to have your work graded and returned to you promptly. Smaller assignments (2 pages or less) should be returned within one week, but it will take up to two weeks for papers and exams. I will notify you of any delays. Your end-of-semester grade will not be rounded up to the next letter grade unless the following conditions are met: You are within one-half of a percent (0.5%) of the next letter grade. Your attendance, participation, and work over the course of the semester demonstrate reasonable effort and attempts at improvement. All assignments must be originally composed for this class. Assignments submitted from previous classes or current classes without prior discussion will receive a zero . LATE WORK Because most of our work is turned in in person, there will be no extensions or make-up opportunities for in-class work unless you have an excused absence (see attendance policies below). For work submitted online (e.g., our Packbacks), I will grant ONE extension per student, per semester, no questions asked. This extension will be for the following class period (e.g. from a Monday deadline until class starts on Wednesday). Simply email me to let me know you want to use your extensionâ€”you do not even need to tell me why unless you wish to. If you have a family or work emergency, additional extensions can be arranged on an individual basis. ATTENDANCE Attendance is required! I keep track of attendance for every class to help me evaluate participation, so missing class repeatedly will affect your final grade. Additionally, it is in your best interest to be here for as many classes as possible, as we will discuss readings, answer questions, and go over materials not covered in your readings. Excused absences: An excused absence is an absence that does not count against your participation grade, and in which you are able to make up any work that you missed. For your absence to be excused in this class, you need to communicate with me ahead of time , especially if it entails being absent for multiple days (e.g. long-term illness, jury duty, military/National Guard training). Depending on the circumstances, I may ask you for documentation. Regardless, the sooner you communicate about problems that affect your attendance, the easier it is for us to make arrangements. If you do not communicate with me, I canâ€™t excuse the absence! Note: for test days, I require all absences to be documented (e.g., by a doctorâ€™s note). An unexcused absence on test day means that you will receive a zero for the test and will not be able to make it up! Unexcused absences: Unexcused absences are absences that you do not communicate with me about. These absences will affect your participation grade, and I reserve the right to dictate whether and how missed work from these absences may be made up. In general, though, work missed from unexcused absences will not be able to be made up. A note about religious observances: All religious observances are valid reasons to miss class or need extensions. If you need to step into the hallway for scheduled prayer times, leave early to attend a service or ceremony, or miss class for a religious event, just let me know ahead of time. Any work/assignments missed for religious observances can be made up. PARTICIPATION Your participation in this class is graded based on your engagement during in-class activities. If you are an active part of group work, raise your hand to answer questions, or chat with me when I come around to check in, you will earn points for the day (3 pts max per day). Unexcused absences, falling asleep, being disruptive, or goofing around on your devices will all have a negative effect on your participation. You can also earn additional participation points for seeking additional help outside of class hours (e.g. coming to office hours or meeting with me to discuss your paper). I keep track of your attendance and participation in an Excel spreadsheet. Here is the math I will use to calculate this part of your grade: Count all of the points you have earned throughout the semester. This number represents your Total Points (TP). Calculate the total potential number of points you could have earned by adding your â€œPresentâ€ days and your â€œAbsentâ€ days (excluding your â€œExcusedâ€ days) and multiply them by 3 (the max number of points you could earn in a day). This number represents your Potential Points (PP). (TP/PP) * 100 = participation grade ACADEMIC MISCONDUCT AND PLAGIARISM You are expected to turn in your own original work for each assignment and exam. We will discuss citation and ways to avoid accidental plagiarism in class (that is part of what you are here to practice), but intentional copying of other students or online sources is not acceptable. Neither isÂ  the use generative AI to produce class assignments (more details below). HANDLING ACAEMIC DISHONESTY As you might imagine, I think itâ€™s very important for you to do you own original work. As such, I have a series of policies to manage instances of cheating and other academic dishonesty. First offense: you will conference with me to agree on a resolution. Weâ€™ll decide what an appropriate solution is based on the exact issue, but possible actions include supplementary lessons/workshops, alternate assignments, and/or manual re-writes. Second offense: I will file a report for official disciplinary action. I also reserve the right to recommend you for a first offense in severe/egregious cases. All students are deemed by the University to understand that if they are found responsible for academic misconduct, they will be subject to the Academic Misconduct procedures and sanctions, as outlined in the Student Handbook. If you are not familiar with these policies, I encourage you to review them. A NOTE ABOUT AI-GENERATED WORK In general, I am not opposed to using technology as a resource, and that includes AI. Youâ€™ll notice that our Packback software makes use of a type of AI software to help you craft your questions and to help me with the grading (though I obviously have override powers). In these contexts, our technology tools are very beneficial. Having said that, generative software like ChatGPT has evolved to the point where I can no longer easily distinguish between human work and computer workâ€¦ which means that I can no longer have confidence in anything you produce on your computers. This is especially true for the content of this course because US History falls into a more â€œgeneral knowledgeâ€ category (this makes it easier for all sorts of engines and large language models to scrape the internet for you). My current tech policy and reliance on in-class work is a reflection of that situation. Under these circumstances, I will regard all instances of generative AI use as cheating and deal with them under the universityâ€™s academic dishonesty policy (see above). ACCESSIBILITY The university is required (by law!) to accommodate any disabilities that you may have. If you have a disability that qualifies you for academic accommodations, contact the Office of Disability Services: Phone: (704) 678-0040; Email: disability@uncc.edu; In-Person: Fretwell 230. They will provide you with a letter that lists your accommodations, and will notify me so that I can make adjustments to class if necessary. These letters do not disclose what your disability is, so you do not need to worry about your professors knowing sensitive personal information. That said, if you want or need me to know your personal situation so that I can better accommodate you, come and talk to me. However, I will not ask you to disclose sensitive information, and you are welcome to keep your privacy. If you are struggling in class for any reason (medical or otherwise), please let me know! There is a limit to what I can do without an official accommodation letter, but there may be small things that I can change with little effort (ex: fonts on PowerPoints or assignment sheets; transcripts for videos). If you have personal concerns that present obstacles to your academic performance, I will do what I can to help you access the resources you need. I am happy to help support you in any way that I can, including guiding you to resources to manage things that are happening in your life outside of class. You have my promise (as a professional and a person of integrity) that anything you tell me will remain between us unless it is a question of your safety or the safety of others. However, you should be aware that I am a mandated reporter, which means that I am required by law to report instances of suspected abuse and discrimination, especially (but not limited to) those that occur on university property, by university personnel, or at university-sponsored events. I am required to report the following things: Gender-based harassment/discrimination Sexual harassment/abuse Abuse/neglect of children or the elderly NOTE: This syllabus is subject to change at instructorâ€™s discretion. I will notify you of any changes. List of Documents We will be covering the following documents in this class. Please use the links in our Canvas page for all readings; these are PDFs with the excerpts and supporting materials that I want you to have! UNIT 1: English Bill of Rights (1689) Declaration of Independence Articles of Confederation Constitution Federalist Papers (selected excerpts) UNIT 2: Cherokee Nation vs Georgia Ft Laramie Treaty Potowatamie Treaty Andrew Jacksonâ€™s address on Indian Removal Declaration of Sentiments (1848) Emancipation Proclamation Gettysburg Address UNIT 3: Plessy vs Ferguson (1890, excerpts) Chinese Exclusion Act (1882) Takao Ozawa vs US (1925) Unit 4: Letter from a Birmingham Jail Griswold vs Connecticut (1965) Roe vs Wade (1973) Indian Child Welfare Act (1978) Course Schedule **Note: this is an approximation of the subjects and deadlines for each week, but is subject to change. As such, I recommend using this section as a planning tool rather than a consistent reference point. The most up-to-date readings will be posted on Canvas. UNIT 1: FOUNDING DOCUMENTS Week 1: Introduction Week 2: Declaration of Independence Week 3: Confederation and Constitution Week 